Dear Ariane,

Very pleased to have you on board. I've attached a zipfile which contains some papers and a thesis to help get you started, and give some context for the project. The main paper is "Dynamics and determinants of land change in India...", which follows a similar method to the one we are proposing, albeit to investigate a slightly different issue. 

The village-level dataset which will form the basis for the work can be found here:

https://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/data/set/india-india-village-level-geospatial-socio-econ-1991-2001

You will need to register for a NASA Earthdata account. This should be straightforward but let me know if you have any problems. The dataset is divided into states to make it more manageable. For the time being I suggest you start with Uttar Pradesh, a state in northern India where Wouter, Ana, Jimmy O'Keeffe and myself have done a lot of work in the past.

The basic idea of the project will be to overlay phenological metrics (e.g. NDVI, EVI) based on remote sensing data from the MODIS instrument with the polygons of the village level dataset. We'll then do some statistical analysis of the main determinants of the particular NDVI signal (for instance, whether farmers grow two crops in a given year, or only one).

To do the spatial overlay we will need to use Google Earth Engine (https://earthengine.google.com/), which allows you to perform geospatial processing in the cloud and negates the need to download large datasets to your computer. The sort of analysis we're proposing is beyond the capabilities of a normal desktop computer. You will need to register for an account, which may take a couple of days. There is a "Getting started" tutorial here:

https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/getstarted

You should be able to see the other documentation topics on the left hand side. The MODIS images will be stored as an ImageCollection (https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/ic_creating), and the village polygons as a FeatureCollection (https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/feature_collections). The overlay will be done using reduceRegion (https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/reducers_reduce_region, https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/reducers_reduce_regions).

See how you get on! There will inevitably be a learning curve, but once you get the hang of it I think it's relatively straightforward.

